WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:07.120
Hello. Thanks, everyone, for coming. So Ryan wanted you to imagine that you were babies.

00:00:07.120 --> 00:00:12.480
I would like you to imagine that you are students in my Intro, Stats, and Data Science class.

00:00:13.200 --> 00:00:18.799
So we're about four weeks into the semester. This means you've learned how to wrangle and

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:24.959
summarize data using dplyr. You can make beautiful visualizations with ggplot2.

00:00:25.680 --> 00:00:32.720
And now I'm going to give you a new-to-you dataset on trees in Portland's parks.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:37.279
I'm going to ask you a more open-ended question than I have so far. I'm going to ask you to just

00:00:37.279 --> 00:00:45.279
do some exploratory data analysis on these trees. And what I want you to just ponder for a moment

00:00:45.279 --> 00:00:51.200
as my student four weeks into the semester, whether or not you feel ready to explore these data.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:56.160
And when I say a moment, I really do mean just a moment, because I'm now going to show you a

00:00:56.160 --> 00:01:03.119
couple of the typical responses I've gotten from students when I did just this. All right.

00:01:03.119 --> 00:01:08.959
So one of my students decided to take two quantitative variables and make a scatter plot.

00:01:08.959 --> 00:01:14.959
That's the appropriate graph. And they went a step further. They realized there were lots of

00:01:14.959 --> 00:01:19.120
points, so they tried to deal with the overplotting by making the points transparent.

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:27.760
They know I love colors, so they customized the color with a hex code. And so their graph really

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:35.040
looks pretty good. But then we get to their explanation. And we see that it says, here's

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:42.400
a graph of the dbh and the crown with ew. We can see that as the dbh increases, so does the crown

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:49.120
with w. All right. So this is not as bad as just saying, as x increases, so does y. They use the

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:55.040
variable names. But I don't really get a sense of these trees. I don't feel like we learned anything

00:01:55.040 --> 00:02:03.199
about the trees from their interpretation of their graph. Another student decided to look at species

00:02:03.199 --> 00:02:08.960
and to see what types of trees there are in Portland. And honestly, I was pretty impressed

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:13.759
with their data wrangling skills, right? They found that there were lots of different species.

00:02:13.759 --> 00:02:19.919
So after they counted them up, they subsetted down to just the five most common. And then they even

00:02:19.919 --> 00:02:27.600
sorted their bar graph based on frequency. Wonderful. Used a lovely color again. But again,

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:34.399
their interpretation of their graph, they noticed we have a lot of these PSME trees. I'm not a

00:02:34.399 --> 00:02:39.679
botanist. I don't think the student here was either. We don't have a great sense of trees in

00:02:39.679 --> 00:02:48.639
Portland. All right. But you know what? This is not my students' fault. They've done what I've taught

00:02:48.639 --> 00:02:56.000
them to do. I have taught them to wrangle code. I've taught them to make graphs. And I gave them

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:04.080
a one-sentence explanation of this data. So maybe it's obvious to all of you. It should have been

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:11.919
obvious maybe to me. But to do good data work, we need context. And I was not providing my students

00:03:11.919 --> 00:03:17.839
with enough context to go to the last step and to actually tell stories with their data.

00:03:19.199 --> 00:03:27.839
But you know what? Providing good context is tough and sounds exhausting. If you've ever taught an

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:34.000
intro stats and data science course, I already have jammed enough things into that class, right?

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.800
I have to teach them all of the statistical concepts. I have to teach them how to code. And

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:45.759
now I also have to teach them about the data. So I'm going to admit to you that I mostly ignored

00:03:45.759 --> 00:03:52.559
this problem. Sure, instead of a sentence, I started giving them a paragraph about the data.

00:03:52.559 --> 00:03:58.320
And I would link out to where I got the data from. But I'm going to tell you right now that

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:05.039
their interpretations of their summary statistics and their graphs didn't really improve very much.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:14.960
Until I had to co-lead a workshop on teaching intro stats with R. So this was two instructors

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:19.920
who most of them had been teaching intro stats for quite a while. But they were new to R.

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:25.119
They were new to coding. It was a half-day workshop. And you know what I didn't want to

00:04:25.119 --> 00:04:31.119
have to do in this half-day workshop? I did not want to teach these people file paths.

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:38.959
I did not want to spend an hour of the workshop just loading the data in. I needed to teach them

00:04:38.959 --> 00:04:48.160
how to wrangle and summarize and model and visualize data, right? And so my co-instructor

00:04:48.160 --> 00:04:54.239
said, hey, Kelly, you have that really cool data set on trees in Portland. How about you turn that

00:04:54.239 --> 00:05:00.399
into an R data package? Because you got this train ride coming up, you can just do it on the train.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:10.320
All right. So my first R data package was created called pdxtrees. I have a public GitHub repository

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:15.760
where the participants in my workshop, but also all of you, can learn about the package.

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:23.119
Being a good data scientist, I made a hex sticker. If you're like, hmm, what in the world is going

00:05:23.119 --> 00:05:28.880
on with that hex sticker and those colors? Well, if you've never been to Portland's airport,

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:34.399
it is fashioned after the PDX airport carpet. Now I'm all worried that you're going to go to

00:05:34.399 --> 00:05:38.799
Portland's airport and you're going to be like, that's not the carpet. It is true. They ripped up

00:05:38.799 --> 00:05:44.000
our beloved carpet. I think there's like one terminal that still has it. But this is my

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:51.440
favorite Portland carpet. Okay. So my first R data package was born, and this solved our problem.

00:05:52.079 --> 00:06:00.079
They could install the package, and then they all had the same code to load the data set. I didn't

00:06:00.079 --> 00:06:05.760
have to teach them about file paths. And we could go through the workshop then, and they could learn

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:12.880
to wrangle and visualize and model and summarize the data. Okay. But there was a really lovely

00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:20.880
side effect of creating an R data package. As I told you, I made a readme. So I shared that URL,

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:27.279
which had the readme as the landing page where they could learn more about the data set. And then

00:06:27.279 --> 00:06:33.200
as they were using the data set, if they had a question about a particular variable, they could

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:40.320
just do question mark and the function name, and they could learn about that variable. Very simply.

00:06:40.320 --> 00:06:48.320
Okay. So now that I had this R data package that I used, sure, originally for a workshop,

00:06:48.320 --> 00:06:55.679
I now use it in my classes. And I have to say that the students' interpretations of their work

00:06:55.679 --> 00:07:02.160
has improved massively. So the student that now decides to make a scatter plot, again, of these

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:08.880
two variables, tells me a lovely story about the trees. As the diameter of the tree increases,

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:13.040
well, it makes sense that the canopy is going to get larger. We're going to have more branches

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:18.640
and leaves and foliage. We don't have to be a botanist for that to make sense. We can now start

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:27.519
to actually see the trees. And that most common tree? Well, that's Douglas fir. Douglas fir is

00:07:27.519 --> 00:07:32.399
Oregon state tree. It makes sense that it was the most common tree in our data set.

00:07:32.399 --> 00:07:41.200
All right. So context is key to doing good data work. And what I learned is because the context

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:48.799
is so close to the data in an R data package, that is a great way to give people access to

00:07:48.799 --> 00:07:56.239
the context, the story of the data. And then I went a step further, not with my intro students,

00:07:56.239 --> 00:08:01.440
with my second semester students. I decided once I'm now teaching students about data management

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:07.760
and data sharing, I should be teaching them to share their data with R data packages. And I will

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:13.600
say their favorite part of the project is creating their hex sticker. So here are just a selection of

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:21.119
hex stickers from my students over the years. Okay. Let's talk about how to make an R data package.

00:08:22.079 --> 00:08:27.359
First, all right, this seems obvious, but you need to have a data set that you want to share with

00:08:27.359 --> 00:08:33.919
others. So I'm going to just admit to you all, I had not bought a new pair of jeans since before

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:40.640
the pandemic. I was really dreading it. And so I was a good data scientist, and I went on

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:45.280
Anthropology's website and did what any data scientist would do, and I created a data set

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:53.599
of jeans. Spoiler alert, people really like wide leg jeans nowadays. Okay. That's a thing.

00:08:53.599 --> 00:09:00.479
Leg opening. All right. So now I want to share this jean data set with others so that when they

00:09:00.479 --> 00:09:06.320
want to go shopping for jeans, it's not as painful. All right. So let's put this data in an R data

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:13.919
package. I'm going to admit something right now. I am not about to go through all of the steps to

00:09:13.919 --> 00:09:20.719
make an R data package because you should not learn how to make an R data package by passively

00:09:20.719 --> 00:09:26.479
sitting there and watching me talk through the steps. Instead, you should learn from the pros.

00:09:27.119 --> 00:09:34.000
But even still, you should not sit here and listen to Jenny and Hadley tell you the steps to make an

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.880
R data package. What you should do is you should go get their book, which you can read for free

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:44.000
online, and they actually go through the steps. So you should actively go through the steps of

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:49.280
creating a package. Now, their book is about making R packages in general, but they have

00:09:49.280 --> 00:09:55.840
sections specifically about how to put data into your package. So instead, what I want to focus on

00:09:55.840 --> 00:10:03.359
are some of the tips and the documentation. So in terms of tips, I recommend that you lean heavily

00:10:03.359 --> 00:10:13.039
on the wonderful helper functions that are out there. Dev tools use this. R oxygen 2. I just

00:10:13.039 --> 00:10:18.640
don't understand. I'm from Iowa. I'm going to pronounce things however I want. But these helper

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:24.080
packages are really useful. They streamline the process. They automate a lot of the steps.

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:30.559
They just make it easier to go from raw data to finished package. The other tip I have for you is

00:10:30.559 --> 00:10:38.000
that there are lots of wonderful R data packages out there. So mimic them. In particular, the

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:44.400
Palmer Penguins package has wonderful documentation inside. And so I always have my students, when

00:10:44.400 --> 00:10:49.679
they're working on this project, go look at some of these packages, go to their GitHub repositories,

00:10:49.679 --> 00:10:56.960
and see how they're actually talking about the data. Okay. But as I said, what I want to focus

00:10:56.960 --> 00:11:03.440
on in terms of the package development is creating good documentation. Because that is really the

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:09.359
piece that is so wonderful about an R data package. I'm going to talk about three different types of

00:11:09.359 --> 00:11:15.280
documentation. And I'll show just a little bit of code that you can use to help with that process.

00:11:16.159 --> 00:11:21.679
So let's start with the readme. You've already seen the readme for my pdxtrees R data package.

00:11:22.479 --> 00:11:27.919
We need to now make a readme for the genes package. To get the skeleton of a readme,

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:35.520
you can use the use readme RMD function. And so the way I want us to think about the readme is,

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:42.479
all right. I'm on anthropology's website. I've got a sea of genes in front of me. And I see one

00:11:42.479 --> 00:11:48.159
I think I might be interested in. So there's that nice little button, the quick view button,

00:11:48.719 --> 00:11:54.960
which will pull up just a small page that tries to give me the essential information I need to

00:11:54.960 --> 00:12:01.200
decide whether or not I want to look at that gene more or less. Or if I want to move on to some other

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:07.039
pair. So I want you to think about the readme as the quick view. You're trying to help the user

00:12:07.039 --> 00:12:12.880
decide very quickly whether or not they should be interested in your package. So you want to give

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:19.760
them a big picture overview of what the package does, how they can install it, and maybe a simple

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:26.400
example of how they could use your package. Okay? So we have that for our genes. Someone decides,

00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:31.760
all right, yes, I am interested in this package. I'm going to install it. I'm going to load it.

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:37.840
So now we should move on to the help file. So the help file is our next layer in to help them get a

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:44.880
better sense of this package and the data inside. The use R function is useful for creating the

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:50.559
shell of where you're going to put the contents of your help file. You'll put in some R oxygen

00:12:50.559 --> 00:12:55.679
code. And then you'll run the document function to turn that into the help files we're used to.

00:12:55.679 --> 00:13:00.880
So that when someone does question mark genes, they'll see the help file for this data set.

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:06.880
And the way I like to think about the help file is this is like when I now clicked on that genes

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:15.280
actual page, I get the product details, right? I get to learn about what it's made out of. Was it

00:13:15.280 --> 00:13:21.679
made in the U.S.? What's the style? So on and so forth. That's the same idea as the help file,

00:13:21.679 --> 00:13:26.479
right? I get to learn about each of the individual variables. What's the class of those

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:32.320
variables? What's the values it can take on? How many genes are in my data set? So I get a sense

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:38.320
of how I could use this. What are the variables present? Why would I want to interact with this

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:44.559
data set? So now I've decided I want to interact with it. I have a better sense of it. But I would

00:13:44.559 --> 00:13:50.320
like to see some examples. Now, you can put examples in your help file. But maybe I want

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:55.440
to have more fully fleshed out examples. So vignettes were brought up at the end of the last

00:13:55.440 --> 00:14:02.159
talk. So vignettes are going to be the last type of documentation that I'll mention. And the way

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:07.359
so the use vignette will again make the shell of a vignette for you that you can fill in.

00:14:07.359 --> 00:14:13.840
And the way I want us to think about the vignette is on anthropology's page, underneath that project

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:21.039
details, they have this lovely ways to wear section where they'll show the jeans with different

00:14:21.039 --> 00:14:27.440
shirts and shoes and accessories. Yes, they're just trying to get you to buy more on their website.

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:34.479
But it's giving you concrete ideas on how you could wear those jeans. That's the same purpose

00:14:34.479 --> 00:14:40.320
our vignette should be serving. It should give the user concrete ideas on how they could use

00:14:40.320 --> 00:14:44.880
our dataset. How they could wrangle or visualize or model this dataset.

00:14:46.880 --> 00:14:53.440
Okay. So I just have a few final thoughts I want to share with all of you around R data packages.

00:14:54.799 --> 00:15:01.599
So I did tell Nick this. But I'm also going to tell all of you, it took me longer than a three-hour

00:15:01.599 --> 00:15:07.440
train ride to create my first R data package. There are just errors you're going to run into

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:16.400
that you have not seen before. And the Wi-Fi on Amtrak is terrible. So that's true.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:22.799
But after I made my first package, making the second and so on went much, much faster.

00:15:22.799 --> 00:15:29.200
And much more smoothly. And so my biggest piece of advice, if you're going to make an R data

00:15:29.200 --> 00:15:36.000
package is make it with someone else who's already made one before. Because once you hit some weird

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:41.280
snag, they can come in, look over your shoulder and tell you what you're missing. So this is

00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:47.039
really important to me in terms of teaching my students how to make these. So the first day of

00:15:47.039 --> 00:15:53.599
class or the first day of the project, we actually during the class period all make the same package

00:15:53.599 --> 00:16:00.559
from start to finish using the whole game chapter of Hadley and Jenny's book. So that again, I'm

00:16:00.559 --> 00:16:05.679
around when they, you know, on step four forget to put quotes in the name of the package at the

00:16:05.679 --> 00:16:12.159
end of their script file. I can find these mistakes and help them see that really they have the skills

00:16:12.159 --> 00:16:17.280
and the tool set to make a package. But again, I think it's really important to have someone around

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:24.719
who can help you troubleshoot errors. And then I want to talk about that lonely CSV for a moment.

00:16:25.359 --> 00:16:31.679
You're going to still share data as lonely CSVs. I absolutely still do that with my students. I

00:16:31.679 --> 00:16:38.000
don't just give them data from R data packages in part because after they leave my class,

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:43.280
people are not going to share data with them always with R data packages. So it's okay to

00:16:43.280 --> 00:16:51.119
give people CSVs, but it is important that we are investing time in the context so that when we share

00:16:51.119 --> 00:16:57.039
data with others, with our students, our collaborators, frankly ourselves, we actually

00:16:57.039 --> 00:17:04.719
are giving people the information they need to do good data work because context really is key

00:17:04.719 --> 00:17:09.920
to doing good data work. Okay. Thank you so much for coming. I do...

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:22.880
So as I said, I really did make that genes demo repo so you can check it out. I also have

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:27.680
hex stickers for my PDX trees package. If you'd like one, come see me after the session.

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:40.160
Okay. We have a few questions in a minute or two. Do you teach about data ownership and how

00:17:40.160 --> 00:17:43.520
you navigate this as students create their own packages?

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:50.079
Yeah. So I mean, like have you ever thought about what license to have, right? So now

00:17:50.079 --> 00:17:54.400
that'll be a question. You're going to get an error when you try to, or at least a warning.

00:17:54.400 --> 00:18:00.000
One of those two, when you tried to build that package, if you've not put a license in there.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.959
And so yes, this is a perfect moment. And I'm going to say, you know what I do when we're

00:18:04.959 --> 00:18:11.359
going to talk about licenses and ownership? I bring a data librarian into the classroom

00:18:11.359 --> 00:18:16.800
because they are much better at talking about that than I am. And so they talk about the

00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:23.359
different types of licenses and what impact that would have downstream on people using the data

00:18:23.359 --> 00:18:25.359
set in your package. Great question.

00:18:27.280 --> 00:18:33.599
Can you talk about having students make their own, how it went for the students?

00:18:33.599 --> 00:18:39.119
Yeah. So, you know, even if on day one, we do a demo where we go from start to finish

00:18:39.119 --> 00:18:43.520
and me and the TAs are walking around the rooms and helping them, you're still going

00:18:43.520 --> 00:18:49.040
to hit snags, right? So, so absolutely there are, there are going to be issues that you

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:55.359
hit along the way. So we would bake sometime into class where, again, they would get to

00:18:55.359 --> 00:19:00.640
work on their, their packages in their groups and I'm walking around the room and helping

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:06.400
them. So I would say with enough scaffolding, it really can go okay, but you do really need

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:12.479
some experts around because you don't want them to then sit in their dorm room, you know,

00:19:12.479 --> 00:19:17.359
for four hours with this one bug that in, you know, two seconds you would be able to

00:19:17.439 --> 00:19:22.640
catch and now just decide like coding is terrible because I can't, I can't get my package to

00:19:22.640 --> 00:19:28.239
compile. So, so yes, you just have to do a lot of scaffolding. My office hours during

00:19:28.239 --> 00:19:32.479
the time when they're working on this package, I always have like muffins and cookies as

00:19:32.479 --> 00:19:37.359
an extra incentive to really get them coming to see me. So, so yes, I think it's just

00:19:37.359 --> 00:19:42.640
all about providing them with the right, right support. And we spend four class periods actually

00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:46.959
learning about the different steps because talking about the documentation and helping

00:19:46.959 --> 00:19:51.760
them write good documentation takes time. So, so you'd still want to also devote a,

00:19:51.760 --> 00:19:54.319
a significant chunk of, of class to this.

00:19:55.040 --> 00:19:57.920
All right, last question. Did any of them send their packages to CRAN?

00:19:58.479 --> 00:20:04.239
Ah, so good question. And you'll notice one piece of documentation I did not talk about

00:20:04.239 --> 00:20:09.760
was making a website with package down. So, right, I give the students ownership over

00:20:09.760 --> 00:20:15.280
whether or not they do want to share things publicly or not. And so we talk about how

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:19.920
you can make a website, but I don't actually require that as part of the project. So at

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:24.319
the end of the project, they all get to decide whether or not as a group, they want to turn

00:20:24.319 --> 00:20:30.239
their GitHub repo to be now public instead of private. But I'm not sure any of them have

00:20:30.239 --> 00:20:35.680
submitted to CRAN yet. So that should be an extra credit point for, for the next iteration.

00:20:36.959 --> 00:20:38.400
They should get free tuition for that.

00:20:40.319 --> 00:20:41.280
Above my pay grade.

00:20:41.280 --> 00:20:49.760
Let's thank Kelly again.

